The Czech Social Democrats in Prague know neither Voldemort nor the "Konditorei".
The new City Council leaders from the ČSSD will obviously have to overcome certain language barriers in order to understand their old and new colleagues from the ODS in the Prague Council and the City Council.
The newspaper Aktuálně.cz has been a little "tapping" on the new council members from the ČSSD as they master the notorious slang that has become naturalized in recent years, when today's coalition partners were at the helm in Prague.
The coded vocabulary, introduced by the Prague political elite in the era of former mayor Pavel Bém, is borrowed from some of the best known actors, situations and causes.
The new councils were surprisingly somewhat in the dark about these new concepts.
At least that's what they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"I have no idea".
"I'm more of a novice in Prague politics", said Lukáš Kaucký, the new Minister of Culture, in response to the test of the "patent vocabulary".
But the councilor Karel Březina - a political veteran - reacted in a similar way.
For example, the term "golf hole".
"That's the only expression of the ones you present to me here that I use now and then".
"Other than that, I don't think much of slang".
From the glossary published by the daily Aktuálně.cz in June this year before the ODS election congress, the editors picked out six terms, especially those that are notoriously associated with the Prague Magistrate.
The Social Democrats should define the terms "Voldemort", "the biggest Prague golf hole", "go to the pastry shop", "bullshit", "treason against the capital" and "blank".
Three Prague councillors agreed to the test, while the fourth - Antonín Weinert, the future head of the Prague school system - first promised to participate in the conversation, but then did not even take the phone.
The fifth councilor, Petr Dolínek, rejected the test from the start.
"I don't care about these things and how the bourgeois democrats talk among themselves, I don't judge them".
"What is important to me is how we understand each other within our programmes", he replied.
As already indicated, in the above-mentioned headline, Lukáš Kaucký allegedly did not realize that the influential businessman and friend of the former Mayor of Bém, Roman Janoušek, was being referred to.
The term "Voldemort" doesn't tell Kaucky anything, and the only term he guessed correctly on the test was "the biggest golf hole in Prague".
"This is the Blanka tunnel", Kaucký says, adding, "but I know it from the newspaper".
And jokingly, "I guess I'll have to take a language course".
The "Golfloch" is then not only deciphered by Matador Karel Březina, but also by the Councilman for environmental issues Lukáš Plachý correctly as Tunnel Blanka.
Both Social Democrats also know who the term Voldemort stands for and Lukáš Plachý even knows where to find this figure and thus what it means to "go to the pastry shop".
"I think that means going to some Prague catering establishment", Plachý is pretty close to solving the riddle, if you know that this is the seat of Janoušek's companies.
In agreement with Březina, however, he claims to have extracted this knowledge from the newspaper rather than that this vocabulary was his own.
The results of the survey show that the Social Democrats do not have a similarly integrated group.
"I asked my colleagues, but obviously we don't have that kind of thing".
"We call each other by name, and occasionally we use abbreviations or nicknames", says Prague's ČSSD chairman Petr Hulínský - known as "Hulda" by his party colleagues.
"In school, I was called Bříza (Birch), but I don't know if my colleagues call me that", says Karel Březina, who shares his nickname.
The newspaper Deník Aktuálně.cz tried the name and look - it works.
Ratsherr Weinert is friendly to the party members as the "Opa" or less friendly as the "Alte", the representative Miroslav Poche, who drew attention to himself before the elections by scheming in party sponsorship, is called by some colleagues "Igráček" (known Czech Lego figure).
The only thing the Social Democrats allow in the internal party language is nicknames.
Hulínský reportedly does not like being called "Hulda", but Deník Aktuálně.cz registered another nickname of the Prague chairman.
His nickname "Doctor of Rubber Butt Law" is allegedly related to the fact that Petr Hulínský acquired his title of Doctor juris at the Bratislava Police Academy.
The government wants to stop torturing "witches" and has published a brochure
Women who are branded as witches in Burkina Faso tend to share some common social characteristics.
They are more likely to be of the older generation, they cannot find work - for example, for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
If any of these women "become" a witch, they are strictly isolated so that they cannot become a danger to the rest of the village.
"Men are rarely affected by this fate".
"Even young and healthy women are spared this, as they help with the work and give birth", describes a nun who cares for more than a hundred women who have been cast out of their communities in a special home in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso.
The local government decided to take action against this abnormal "social measure".
And that's why he put out a pamphlet to stop the witch-hunt.
But there's a catch.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read", noted the newspaper derStandard, pointing to the dilemma of literacy.
But accusations of witchcraft are common in other African lands as well.
In Ghana, the neighboring country of Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmahová, 27, was tortured to death by three women and two men - they poured petroleum on her and simply set her on fire.
This incident was reported by the BBC server among others.
The perpetrators, however, claimed that the incident was just a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to their version, the oil that is used for ritual anointings is ignited.
This was after the group had tried to "expel an evil spirit" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by the people here, regardless of their education.
The Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: "The human soul-snatching business was once as dangerous as it is now".
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to reduce the witch-hunt, the Gambian President has been very much involved in the affair himself over the past year.
"President Yahya Jammeh has launched a monstrous witch hunt after the death of his aunt, alleging that they were responsible for her death and would now try to kill the president himself with black magic".
"He called for the help of shamans from neighbouring Guinea, who, accompanied by police, soldiers and the president's bodyguard, violently abducted indiscriminately detained women and men from Gambian villages and brought them to the president's farm in Kanilai", Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the prisoners were forced to drink a potion made from plants that had hallucinogenic effects but also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the people arrested did not survive the farm.
It was only as a result of international pressure that the nearly one thousand prisoners were released.
A tenant of Bakala: He heats in the oven - but still pays higher rent
An elderly sub-contractor is leaving the client center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal baron" Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of apartment buildings in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm, a briefcase with three new leases for three apartments: his own and his daughters' apartments, and his son, who is currently serving a prison sentence.
The three of them have just been given rent increases as part of the so-called deregulation.
Instead of a monthly rent of 3500 krones, the son should spend 4100 krones next year for a two-room apartment with a second-class kitchen.
"And there's not even hot water in the apartment and you have to heat it in a simple coal stove", he angrily taps his finger on his son's new lease, which he has the power to sign.
"But what - I signed it", he explains half-displeased and half-resigned.
The citizens' association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new lease terms "incorrect and immoral", advises tenants not to sign the new lease contracts and to wait until December 7, when it plans to publish a guide on how to deal with such contracts.
But the man just waves.
"One says this, the other says that", he makes a gloomy face.
The Ostrava region is thus becoming a major 'de-regulation laboratory'.
After the new year, this deregulation will affect most of the rental apartments in the Czech Republic, whose tenants have not paid market rent until now.
Aktuálně.cz therefore decided to visit this "laboratory" in person.
The RPG waiting room in Havířov is one of four in the Ostrava region and already at 9 am this Tuesday it is packed to capacity.
Right next to the door are the bodyguards of a security agency and a pager.
"Rent 2011", a special touch screen is illuminated.
A little tap and the machine spits out a number.
We've barely deciphered the number "157" and it's already beeping on the big screen on the ceiling of the waiting room.
Half a second later, it's your turn.
A little later, an elderly couple enter the waiting room to ask about the rent, but the storm in the waiting room does not seem to apply to the new rent.
Most people are here to solve the usual problems - repair requests, insurance matters and so on.
From mid-November, envelopes with the new leases start to arrive in the mailboxes of most of the tenants of the total of 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio in the Ostrava region.
RPG Byty proposed in the letter a rent increase of between 15 and 38%.
The special desk for new rentals in the customer centre has been open since 18 November.
"The action has been going on for a little over a week, so this is just the beginning", the ladies behind the counter reply after a moment of hesitation, when the "client" reveals himself as a journalist.
Deregulation and the former miners' residences in Bakala are a hot topic.
Before the elections, the deputy speaker of the Parliament Lubomír Zaorálek from ČSSD, who is from Ostrava, took up this issue quite loudly, and it is no wonder that the newspapers are full of it today.
"For 20 years I've been asking them to give me a new floor".
"No shit. They could have changed toilet glasses", the man mentioned at the beginning of the article breathes.
So far, according to the employees, it is mainly pensioners who are waiting at the counter to see if they will really get the promised rent reduction that RPG promises them if they sign the special offer on time.
The other tenants who sign the new lease agreement by 15 December will also benefit from a half-rate in February.
So far, however, the "de-regulation switch" in Havířov is far from overwhelmed by demand.
"Of yesterday's 360 clients, only about 40 to 50 were due for rent in 2011", the counter clerks estimate.
RPG offers individual rental agreements where it considers this to be necessary, both on its websites and on its wall boards.
If the parties do not agree on the new rent, it will be determined by an independent court.
"This is not meant to be a threat, but rather to be understood as information about the only possible and completely legitimate legal procedure", RPG explains on its website.
"No one is going to court here", says one of the RPG Byty employees, and a man on the street outside the customer service center agrees with her, at least in part.
"I have a pension of 13,000 (Kronas), 5,000 of which are left over for food, where would I get the money for a lawsuit", he says.
That's what makes the employee feel insecure.
"Let me see".
"Mr Zaorálek tells them through the media not to sign and so people are waiting", she adds.
The regulated rent will end in most of the Czech Republic on New Year 2011 and according to RPG Byty the rent increase is an economic necessity.
"The existing rent level is not even enough to maintain the housing fund", argues Pavel Klimeš, the director of the housing portfolio of RPG Byty, and - precisely the neglect of the housing fund, which is criticized by the rented tenants, is the main reason for the rent increase, according to the homeowners.
While RPG was able to invest four billion in the apartments from the rentals received between 2005 and 2010, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 it is expected to be 5.2 billion.
The large LCD display on the ceiling opposite the armchairs in the waiting room of Havířov occasionally shows a few red-lit information.
'The rent increases of 15% and below in 2011 concern 31200 flats, i.e. more than 90% of RPG's flats.'
'This always means no more than CZK 7.50 per square metre per month' reads the LCD monitor.
Only 400 apartments in RPG's portfolio will increase rents by 38 percent.
"In these cases, the issue is the increase of extremely low rents of CZK 19.66 per square metre", argues RPG.
The rent will stay the same next year for 2,600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not drive rents up by leaps and bounds, but will be gradual over four and eight years.
What is more, the company imposes a further commitment: all the revenue from the increase in rent (see diagram) the company wants to put back into the apartments, mainly in heat savings - in new windows and in thermal insulation.
But, first and foremost, these are supposed to benefit the people who sign the agreements on the rent increase.
The architects saw - the office includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini-kindergarten with all the necessary features - colorful walls, creative furniture, lots of toys, and even a mini-playground on the patio?
This kindergarten has been available to the Arch.Design staff since last year.
The design and architecture firm Arch.Design, whose studios have produced a number of well-known Brno buildings, has been planning for the premises for its company mini-kindergarten from the first designs for the new Avriopoint building.
This is a good sign, because most of its 90 employees are of baby-boom age and the company is keen to get the designers and architects back to work as soon as possible.
The possibility of working part-time is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of its social programme.
This makes it easier for civil engineers and architects to combine their demanding profession with childcare.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of the Arch.Design staff and with the support of the management, they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The company-based mini-kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
This financing (grants of CZK 2.8 million) has enabled the necessary facilities and equipment to be procured and has provided for qualified staff and operations for a period of 2 years.
After the aid has been used up (for two years), Arch.Design is obliged to continue to run the mini-kindergarten for another three years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the Economy Rating company providing active assistance in the application process.
The children are cared for by a qualified staff, a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, and there are no age restrictions for children, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini-kindergarten, only five children can be present at a time, but several children take turns during the day.
The kindergarten is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, and the children of all employees have the same rights in the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is an individual education and care programme, the content of the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework programme of pre-school education.
The children are not only playing but are also receiving excellent instruction, from basic knowledge to preschool education, and they are learning English in the process.
The classroom is equipped not only with toys and creative games, but also with a computer that is available to the children.
What is more, the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company atmosphere.
Parents can keep an eye on their children at all times, eliminating the stress of delayed pick-ups from a distant kindergarten.
Parents therefore use their working time more productively.
It is no wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relations are also formed here.
Arch.Design thus joined the ranks of Czech companies that offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and through such programmes strengthen their HR marketing.
A house of bones still fascinates after 100 years.
The roof is like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs are like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are ripped fish lips.
This is the Casa Batlló by Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
The local inhabitants nicknamed the house with its organic forms "Knochenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tiles and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of scales and the ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The house's facade plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures that evoke nature and living beings.
It's only when you look closely that you realize that everything is governed by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the entire facade is even more plastic, dramatic, and the special lighting enhances the brilliance of the colors.
The same sweeping lines and intricate shapes dominate the interior of the house.
Wavy wood is used for window frames, railings, and door ornaments, as well as for peepholes and railings.
The Batlló house in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was created by the conversion of a house from 1877, carried out by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but eventually agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of reality came into being, and the use of mosaics on the facade was also his idea.
However, many other artists and painters also contributed to the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed "Knochenhaus" (Bone House) by the local inhabitants because of its organic forms.
Others called it "the passing house" because of the special window opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of Saint George, patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted on the top of the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system for the house, unique at the time, with vents and typical chimneys.
Something bizarre is suggesting its 45-degree inclination.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building codes of the time and was not distracted by them.
He obtained the city's building permit before construction began, but the details he gave about the planned reconstruction were so vague that when it was completed two years later, the city fathers were so horrified by the result that they demanded remedies.
The councilors also found that the building with its pillars even invaded the public sidewalk.
The changes were not, however, to the contrary - only fifteen days after the request from the neighbourhood, Josep Batlló applied for permission to rent the two highest floors of the building - and it was promptly granted.
The owner of the house moved into the lower floors.
The gallery on the second floor was a social hall, and the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment were on the third floor.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building is a stairway up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reconstruction eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
But Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the drawing-room doors, and so a larger company could chat comfortably without having to forego a certain intimacy in more intimate conversations.
The house received Gaudí's remodeling, which, in addition to a new facade, also added a rather unusual roof and two more floors.
Also impressive are Gaudí's play with light, the blue and white glazed tiles that cover the inner courtyard and the lanterns.
The play of these two colors brings the maximum amount of light to all the floors of the house.
He simply used the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which absorb sunlight.
Casa Batlló, which was added to the Unesco World Heritage List in 2005, is now open to visitors.
On the first floor, the most spacious and sumptuous apartment is open to the public.
The owners decided to do this in the year of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was determined that this was a very profitable business, the inspections were continued, and indeed they were extended to other common areas and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price for visiting the monument is not a paperweight, however, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes get a 20 percent discount.
This is more than the entrance fees for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to experience the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the residents and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed frame?
It's not the best bed frame, but the quality of the bed - so a mattress and a bed rack make a good bed.
The Commission's proposal is to be submitted to the Council by the end of the year.
Many factors are involved in the selection - the weight, height, health status, and not least the sex of the sleeper.
Equally important is the interior, in which mattresses and bed rails have to be subordinate.
Typical example?
Latex mattresses are not suitable for a weekend home that is not regularly heated, as they take much longer to "get warm".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be changed regularly.
If they do not have enough air ducts in the core and are placed on a solid surface, moisture accumulates, so it is possible that mold may form under them.
Of course, what you are used to also plays a role in the choice.
If you have been abroad for a long time, where very high soft-coated mattresses are common, you will find it difficult to get used to a low hard-coated mattress.
"Well, all the hockey players who came back from the NHL have been complaining to me that they can't sleep properly here anymore".
"They just need a soft layer of memory foam for their shaved shoulders, heels, and hips".
"I recommend it to people with diabetes, who suffer from a nervous system disorder, which makes it difficult for them to receive the 'information' from the joints and skin", explains Sylva Hadamcziková, a specialist in upholstered furniture.
That's why I've been getting these memory foam mattresses to many hockey players and other customers for years.
"Today, this is no longer a problem, as mattresses of this type are offered by the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex and the Czech manufacturer Tropico, among others".
And you don't have to be a famous ice hockey player to appreciate the benefits of visco-foam.
This "miracle" is actually quite simple.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the heat absorbed, in other words, it adheres to the warm body.
Nowhere is it crowded, no turning around in the night like after a heavy battle.
You sleep a lot better.
The viscoelastic foam also provides protection against decubitus (wound burn).
When choosing the size of the mattress, the length of the soles of the feet should always be added to the height of the body, i.e. approximately 21 to 34 cm.
A man or woman who is about six feet tall needs a bed that is about six to eight feet long.
Each of the slaughterers should have at least 90 cm of bed space, i.e. 180 cm in total.
For single beds, for example singles, 120 to 140 cm are appropriate.
For your comfort and for any visitors you might have.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal bed width: "When you are lying on your back, there should be enough space for slightly angled arms", advises Helena Prokopová, the master of upholstery and interior design, who has been working on the problem of healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture for many years and also lectures on this subject at specialist schools.
In a double bed, each person needs his own bed and mattress, but be careful when shopping to ensure that the mattresses are of the same height.
Otherwise, the only option is to mount the grating at different heights, and this is not possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with a spring skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimetres should be on the mold layer and the fine upholstery.
"You should never touch the feathers with your hand or when sitting down", warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a specific type of grate.
Fully-mattressed beds with mattresses and pillows like conjoined Siamese twins are not to be found in the bedroom.
These mattresses can't be aired and the upholstery can't be washed, which is commonplace today.
And since you lose between 0.2 and 0.75 liters of sweat in a single night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress will slowly become a huge (and clogged) sieve.
That is why experts reject advertising slogans that promise a lifespan of up to 25 years or even a lifetime warranty on mattresses.
Everything has its ifs and buts.
And so a practical tip from the dealers: For a 120 or 140 cm wide mattress, you should not be afraid of the hygiene of washable, removable linings, but it is still advisable to use a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although today mattress covers are usually made with a round-off, so that after opening you get two halves (very important for the washing process and the washing machine size!), the manipulation with larger mattresses, especially carried out alone, often resembles the unequal battle between David and Goliath.
Do they have a solid plate in the bed instead of a rust one?
Get it out!
Or at most for a bed for unwelcome guests and for a single night.
Even so, they should preferably provide the slab with ventilation holes (if they do not already have any) and use mattresses with spring skeleton and a minimum height of 15 cm with so-called pocket feathers and fine padding.
Polyurethane mattresses do not fit on such a substrate.
For non-adjustable latten bars with 14 to 18 spring bars (lamels), latex or sandwich mattresses are suitable (possibly also combinations of latex and coconut), always pay for bars with a larger number of bars, i.e. from 28 and more spring bars, with a Lordosen support in the lumbar region and the possibility of regulating the hardness of the bars.
Adjustable slats shall not include mattresses with a spring frame, as they do not respond to ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to the adjustment of the rigidity of the spring-loads, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This is a special attachment of the spring bars, which allows the spring bars to be pressed in or even twisted in such a way that they allow the pointed sinking of the shoulder of the sleeper.
It's a very important thing for men with broad shoulders.
Some mattress manufacturers have even begun to use shoulder-softening in "men's" mattresses.
The ladies are also considered - they are given these soft zones in the hip area.
For the most demanding customers, lattoflex wing support systems or roosts with multitortion contact pads are intended.
The pressure is distributed to several points, which reduces the tension.
- But if you use a bad (too big and bulky) pillow for the right mattress and the right rest, most of the benefits are lost.
Here again, a rule of thumb is that the pillow should support the head, its tips reaching only to the shoulders, so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
Ideally, a pillow should be 50 by 60 cm, as the Scandinavians like.
In the lateral position, the head cushion (together with the shoulder relief zone in the cast or the soft zone in the mattress) should balance the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the old straw bags.
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least mixtures of them.
The new magic word for mattresses is "organic".
Natural oils, such as castor oil and soya oil, are increasingly being used to produce polyurethane foams instead of petroleum.
Soy is used by all known manufacturers.
"Bio means that the mattress core is made of materials of natural origin", explains Petr Vašíček of Tropico Plus.
Natural ingredients are also used in the production of mattress covers - one of the first was aloe vera.
But you can also indulge in microcapsules that give off a fresh scent of forest or lavender while you sleep.
Here, too, a distinction is made between man and woman.
While men use a "cooling" plant extract made from birch leaves to absorb heat and cool the body, women use "warming" covers.
Extracts from red peppercorns stimulate blood circulation, so the weaker sex get comfortable warm while sleeping.
What about today's favorites?
Mattresses made of calcium foam (this has larger pores with destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than commercial polyurethane and also much more flexible).
The combination of the different stiffness of cold foam and visco-foam creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hips and heels are.
For a high-quality mattress, however, you have to pay 7000 krona and more.
However, health mattresses are usually taxed at a lower rate because they are considered as medical devices.
Gumotex was the first Czech company to benefit from this advantage.
You see, saving on the mattress and the rust is not so easy.
Occasionally, there are special offers from manufacturers and retailers offering two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers the Duofreeze mattress with a visco-foam memory hidden in the purchase for CZK 11,990.
The second one is free.
It was the material Tempur that ushered in the era of viscoelastic foams with open cell structure and high density at near-cosmic pace.
No wonder, they were developed for NASA, because the astronauts are exposed to enormous overload during the launch.
Temperature becomes soft in warmth, and hard in cool weather.
It is thus perfectly adapted to the human body and optimally distributes body pressure.
It is therefore not only ideal for preventing pressure burn but also for improving general sleep comfort.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only in mattresses but also in other health products, such as special foot pads, which are intended to provide relief to the legs and vessels.
For example, domestic producers use the Eucatherm C foam, Twinsaver or similar products.
More and more parents want human-monitoring devices to keep their kids under control.
Fears for their children are growing, and more parents are considering using GPS to monitor their children.
The system, originally designed to track cars, is just as good at tracking people, which would also be helpful in such cases, as in the recent disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette case, but soon it won't be bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people are terrified by the case of the missing Anička and are looking for ways to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of violating her privacy.
"We try to tell everyone that this is not about speculation, but about an effective way to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy", says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of GPS tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that there are instances of misuse of such devices, for example, by putting it in someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not seen any such cases".
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons", adds Pilin.
But, he says, the child should always know the purpose of the "box" and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková, however, points out that if a child does not like to wear such a thing, he simply discards it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in deliberately losing certain things when they do not want to be controlled".
"The mobile phones were already a source of great expectations among parents, but they can be turned off as easily as these new surveillance devices", says Bočková.
In your opinion, it is also controversial whether such a facility actually helps in the event of an attack.
"In planned abductions, the abductor virtually always checks whether the child has any electronics with which to track him".
"Today it's the mobile phone".
"If such surveillance devices were more widely used, they would look for them too, since their sale would surely be accompanied by massive advertising".
"In these cases, the criminals are always one step ahead of the police", says the psychologist.
However, she admits that similar devices can be quite helpful in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
