A longer index finger than ring finger means a lower risk of cancer
Men who have a longer index finger than a ring finger are clearly at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
It is thought that this is related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of fingers can serve as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, particularly in men up to 60", said Ros Eeles, a professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick and co-author of the study.
The finger could help determine which men should definitely be tested for prostate cancer, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health problems, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in the UK followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients, as well as 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had a right index finger shorter than the ring finger.
These men had the same risk of prostate cancer as 19 percent of men with the same ring and index fingers.
However, men whose index finger was longer than their ring finger had a 33- percent decrease in risk, and men over 60 had an 87 percent decrease.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which are formed in prenatal age, evidently reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone is the equivalent of a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone in particular accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, told ČTK that he is only vaguely aware of the study, but that he does not believe the link between finger length and cancer risk has been "fully established".
