The democracy movement in Latin America is growing stronger, as is the support for private enterprise.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil's influence is greater than that of the United States.
These are the findings of the Latinobarómetro survey, which was conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been carried out regularly since 1995 and thus reflects the change in opinion in this region.
Two facts stand out in this year's survey, which was conducted in September and October.
First, the good mood in Latin America.
And second, the growing interest in democracy and its key institutions.
In many countries on the Pacific coast of South America, the democratic movement has grown strongly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where the economy has been growing at about 6% a year since 2002, the number of pro-democracy voters has risen from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Mexico, too, is seeing a similar trend, as the economy recovers from last year's sharp decline.
However, only half of those surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, lower than the regional average (see Chart 2).
Some 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with the democratic practice in their country, the same as last year but 25% more than in 2001 (Figure 3).
Some 34% trust their country's Congress and 45% trust their government, both figures are the same as last year but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined efforts to build more democracy.
This continued during the global economic crisis, possibly because Latin American countries experienced only a brief recession and recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor were hooked up to a stronger social network.
(According to UN Economic Commission for Latin America reports this week, the poverty rate in Latin America rose only slightly in 2009 and has fallen again by 32% this year.)
But there are wide differences in mood from country to country (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread sense of progress.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and violent crime has increased, this is less the case.
For the second time since the survey began, many respondents in Latin America see crime as a bigger problem in their country than unemployment (see Figure 5).
About 31% say that they or a family member have been the victim of a crime in the last year, but this is down from 38% last year, the lowest level since 1995.
The increasing economic performance is reflected in the stronger support for the private and market economy: around 71% of respondents across the region indicated that the private sector is essential for development, compared to 56% in 2007 (see Chart 6).
Some 58% said that only the market economy could bring progress to their country, compared with 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are in favour of a private economy), despite the fact that its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, has nationalized many private companies.
Brazil has the largest share in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, on the other hand, see the US as the most influential country, with the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua being taken over by Venezuela.
