Arsenic-resistant microbe could provide new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of an alien bacterial species that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists have discovered this unusual bacterium here on earth, they believe that it is a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered necessary for life.
"This organism has two options".
"It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow".
"This makes it very special, even though it is almost a kind of 'alien' life form", said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report, which appears in the online Thursday edition of the journal Science.
Until now, six basic elements have been considered essential to life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
But scientists have found that the bacteria in Mono Lake, California, continue to grow even after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what else is possible", said co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists must identify life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study is looking at microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference, in which no details of the discovery were revealed, led to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report might be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that organisms in other planetary systems can use other elements to set in motion biochemical processes and that the 'standard elements' that we believe are absolutely necessary for life are not necessarily fixed", said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute of the Open University of Milton Keynes, in the United Kingdom.
Cockel wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel in that it shows that one element can be replaced by another in basic biochemical processes and structures", added Cockell.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she thought that microbes exposed to both might be able to replace one element with the other.
"The main reason arsenic is toxic is that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus".
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another".
"But the difference is so great that arsenic acts differently from phosphorus, and it enters our biochemical system, where it smudges almost everything", explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increased concentration of arsenic, and it adapted and grew.
So while the microbe grows better in phosphorus, the fact that it can survive in arsenic also shows that arsenic-based life forms can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea of substituting arsenic for phosphorus is not new, but there has been no working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so science has assumed that early life forms used it.
"This suggests that life may have evolved differently from the early Earth age", says Forster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simons' research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy, and the National Institutes of Health.
The rest of the stolen show dogs found in Compton.
The remaining two of the four show dogs stolen from a Bellflower motel were found, according to the Los Angeles County Sheriff's office Thursday.
The four show dogs - two Akitas and two Pembroke Welsh Corgis - disappeared on Tuesday when unknown persons stole the 2006 Chevrolet Express-Van in which the animals were housed for the night in front of a Bellflower Motel 6, authorities said.
