The lion roars again after court approval of the MGM restructuring
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light for a fresh start.
A New York bankruptcy judge on Thursday officially approved the Gleibe's "pre-packaged" plan to pay off the company's $5 billion debt and clear the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to launch new movies and TV shows.
According to Thursday's statements, the plan meets the requirements of US bankruptcy law, so there is nothing to stop MGM from rebooting under the leadership of Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, the founders of Spyglass Entertainment.
The number of employees is reduced from over 400 to about 320 people.
For MGM, Chapter 11 does not actually take effect until JPMorgan Chase has completed a planned $500 million bond to fund the new MGM productions.
At the moment, a consortium of investment banks, which is itself contributing $75 million, is running the company.
The studio's restructuring began in May 2009 with the mandate to help the investment bank Moelis & Co, the management company, which was struggling with interest payments of $300 million/year, solve its financial problems.
In August, CEO Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former Enron CEO and restructuring expert best known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis & Cooper's efforts to resolve MGM's financial woes and pay off the studio's more than 140 creditors took longer than expected.
After months of discussions, the parties decided to put the company up for sale at the end of 2009.
But the auction attracted few bidders and no one wanted to pay the $2 billion demanded by the creditors.
In the spring of this year, everything started over again when the MGM team started the restructuring plan, which after months of debate and internal disputes was finally signed by the creditors at the end of October.
When MGM has officially emerged from bankruptcy in the next few weeks, Moelis and Cooper will receive a multi-million dollar bonus for their work.
The share for Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, amounts to $9.5 million.
Cooper, who was paid $375,000 a month to run the company, will receive a "success bonus" of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production at MGM, which has released only one film this year and has a seven- or eight-film annual schedule to hit theaters in early 2012.
They also plan to make two films after "The Little Hobbit" in co-production with Warner Bros.
The studio will need a separate loan of between $265 million and $275 million for its financial share of these two films, which are to be directed by Peter Jackson.
Investor Carl Icahn, who financed about 18% of the MGM loan, tried to merge the studio with Lions Gate Entertainment, of which he is the largest shareholder.
However, the latest negotiations between the two companies did not lead to any result.
