The prosecutor will not prosecute Senator Ensign
Justice Department prosecutors have cleared Senator John Ensign of the charges brought against him after his affair with a former campaign worker and his attempt to lobby her husband, the senator's attorneys announced Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal challenge to Senator Ensign, a Republican from Nevada, who until the scandal made national headlines and put a damper on his career, was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012.
Senator Ensign's office said he was "very pleased" with the verdict after a year of investigation.
The Senate Ethics Committee could still impose a disciplinary penalty.
According to Ensign's lawyers, they were informed by the Department of Justice that the investigation against Senator Ensign had been discontinued and that there were no further charges in this matter.
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The verdict came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who felt there was sufficient evidence that Ensign had violated the lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails and other documents first revealed in October 2009 in the New York Times led to speculation that Ensign Douglas Hampton, one of his election aides, was using lucrative contracts to buy his silence about an affair with Hampton's wife, Cynthia.
Cynthia Hampton served as treasurer during an Ensign election campaign.
Ensign contacted some political friends to get Hampton work, and according to the documents and interviews, he took over Hampton's lobbying for them after the hiring.
As Hampton was recently on Ensign's campaign team, he was banned from lobbying for his former employer or the entire Senate for a year.
According to ethics experts, the unusual agreement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, violated the so-called "ban on revolving-door lobbying".
According to the published evidence, "this appears to be a collusion and a violation of the revolving-door statutes", says Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients targeted by the government.
While the Justice Department officially refused to reveal the reasons for its decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department seems very cautious in bringing political charges after a series of defeats that were followed by the media with great interest, including last year's decision to drop charges against former Senator Ted Stevens for misconduct by the state's attorney.
Lawyers "are obviously terrible", said Melanie Sloan, president of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, an organization that has brought various lawsuits against Mr. Ensign.
"This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them", she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign's lead attorney, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a prosecutor on Monday and another the next day, telling him that the department would not press charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers had cooperated with the prosecutors to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, had "acted in accordance with the law".
Mr. Coggins declined to elaborate on the legal arguments he had presented to the prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable going into the details of the conversations between the Department of Justice and myself, but let me just say that we believe we made the right decision", he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to suspend its investigation of a separate lawsuit by the Ethics Group alleging that a payment of $96,000 by Mr. Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The Election Commission said there wasn't enough evidence to prove that the money was anything other than a gift.
NV Energy, a large Nevada company that has long supported the senator, was one of the companies where Mr. Hampton found lobbyist work thanks to the help of Mr. Ensign.
An e-mail from December 2008 shows that after the firm passed Mr. Hampton off as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensing's Chief of Staff, John Lopez, had a conversation with Mr. Hampton, in which he informed him that he was "going to the Home Office" for a matter.
Mr. Ensign also met with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, for lunch and asked the Secretary of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after it stopped lobbying for Mr. Hampton.
When the first public information about this affair was revealed last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned his Senate seat, where he had been ranked fourth in the Republican Party.
After months of inactivity, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he was seeking a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a police investigation, his press secretary, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped the Ethics Committee would follow the example of the Justice Department very quickly and shut down its investigation.
"Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work in service of the people of Nevada", she said.
Cheshire appeal draws attention on Twitter
Half a dozen of them were huddled in the courtroom.
In a matter of minutes, they were tweeting their accounts of gruesome witness statements.
In the end, the defense said, there were more than 140,000 Twitter messages about the trial of rape and children chained to beds in a house that was engulfed in flames.
On Thursday, the much-awaited trial of Steven J. Hayes, accused of killing three members of a Cheshire, Connecticut family, will officially come to an end as the jury's verdict on the death penalty is overturned.
But Mr. Hayes' lawyers have already filed court papers arguing the grounds for an appeal that will occupy the courts for years.
One of the most provocative reasons is that the intense coverage of the trial - including the extensive use of Twitter by the average reporter - has created a "circus atmosphere" and such widespread, pervasive, and provocative detail that the jury was unduly influenced by public outrage.
This objection could lead the courts of appeal to consider whether the new technologies require new rules in the courtroom.
"As I have experienced during this trial, I believe there is a real danger that the entry of new technologies into the courtroom affects the right of every individual to a fair trial", said Thomas J. Ullman, Mr. Hayes' lead counsel.
The presiding judge, Jon C. Blue of the Supreme Court, briefly rejected the motions by decision last week, saying that the New Media would be "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the jury was driven by passion.
But that was certainly not the final word on the matter.
For decades, litigation has found that reporting on famously infamous cases creates doubts about the fairness of a trial.
In its landmark 1966 decision, the United States Supreme Court overturned the conviction of Dr. Sam Sheppard, a Cleveland osteopath, who allegedly killed his wife, and said in its decision that because of the New Media, there had been a "carnival atmosphere in the courtroom".
Some believe that the television series and the feature film "On the Run" is based on this crime.
Some lawyers say that court challenges to Mr. Hayes' conviction half a century later might follow the argument that new rules have become necessary to regulate the lines of communication from the courtroom, which were unthinkable at the time of Dr. Sheppard's case.
"There is good reason to be concerned about the influence of new media in trials that are followed by a broad public", said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who has researched the death penalty in Connecticut, which he says is arbitrary.
Professor Donohue said some courts of appeal might be fascinated by the idea that restricting instant communication from the courtroom could make trials fairer.
The Twitter case is just one of many that Mr. Hayes' lawyers have been putting together to debate for years and thus delay a conviction.
