The defense also says they would challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty, arguing that the judge mistakenly replaced a juror who had been a critic of the prosecution, and that he unduly pressured the verdict by making the unusual decision to release the jury over the weekend.
The jurors were not isolated.
But perhaps the most interesting is their argument about the impact of extensive reporting on the trial.
In a court appeal filed last month, they noted that the case had dominated the news in Connecticut and was being discussed by candidates during the governor's race and the U.S. Senate race.
They argued that the New Media had continually reignited the flames of emotion over the case.
"Such a daily procession of media men, cameras and reporters outside the courtroom", the lawyers wrote, "has never been seen before in New Haven and perhaps the nation".
Her focus on Twitter reporting is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists said that the claim that these direct news stories were more provocative than reports that are replaced more slowly was a techno-oppositional view that impoverished reporting on future trials.
However, some lawyers said that appeal courts were often confronted with the argument that societal and technical changes required adaptation by the courts.
Mr. Hayer's lawyers are backing that claim.
In their appeal, they referred to the 1966 Supreme Court decision that overturned Dr. Sheppard's conviction for reporting and made it clear that the New Media needed new rules.
"This case", they wrote, "represents Sheppard versus Maxwell for the 21st century".
Can courtesy bridge the gap?
After a campaign of name-calling and negativity, little civility has broken out in Washington this week.
Is this the sign of a real bipartisan cooperation or a moment of illusion before quickly returning to the battle of the parties in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders did not bring any breakthrough on the big issues that were being dealt with during the so-called lame duck session, the end of an administration's non-decision-making period.
From what we hear, it was not a polite discussion between two different sides, nor a consideration of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of partisan pocketing.
The President's public meeting of the Deficit Commission on Wednesday was also civilised, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates a mutual respect that obscures the ideological divide that continues to separate members from one another.
This is hardly enough to say that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a testing phase - one demanding a sign of cooperation and compromise from the other, while the other is trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after a renewed party war.
The meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were therefore limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, donations, health or advocacy, the two sides are miles apart.
Last but not least, the November election was mild in Washington, at least for a short time.
"No question, the tone has changed", said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"This is inevitable after elections.
Elections are a source of partisan passions that die out.
And that's a good thing".
On some issues, especially those on the lame duck session agenda, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution".
Bush's tax cuts are ending at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of them, whether temporarily or permanently.
Similarly, a compromise on the increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because the Republicans cannot afford to believe that they favored tax cuts for the rich while denying aid to unemployed workers.
After the meeting at the White House on Tuesday, optimism has grown that an agreement on these issues can be reached during the lame duck session and the New START treaty ratified at the same time.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the lame duck session" does not necessarily lead to lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
"Once the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation", he said.
Wehner is also sceptical - and this scepticism is shared by many - that politeness leads to true cooperation.
"I see a lot of what's happening between now and 2012 as a prelude, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012", he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the makeup of the new Republican majority in the White House and the Tea Party voters who helped shape it.
As worried as Republican leaders may be about playing too high, they know they have to try to keep their promises to cut government spending and undo health care reform.
These partisan lines are already apparent in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include tax reform and the raising of some taxes, the raising of the retirement age and the reduction of government expenditure.
Vice-Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and have, in their own estimation, pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 votes out of 18 within the Commission to make their plan an official recommendation and they are fighting hard to get anywhere near that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the Council, since there is little leeway or sympathy for compromise on financial issues, at least today.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first battle will be next year in the form of partisan clashes, with Republicans challenging Obama on the state budget, taxes and health care, followed later by a phase of larger bipartisan cooperation.
What will bring about this change?
The public opinion.
It's been proven that despite the partisanship of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
When confrontation leads to a dead end, as it did in 1995, both parties must carefully watch for public reaction.
Whoever is doomed to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there appears to be a larger ideological divide between Obama and the congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists in both parties see 2010 as a prelude to a far more consequential election in 2012.
In this regard, the courtesy displayed this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that continue to divide them.
Leaked US document portrays Moscow as a haven of corruption
The city is controlled by the "Kleptocracy" and they pass some of the bribes and protection money they collect to the Kremlin, the US Embassy in Russia reported in a memo in February.
Both the police and the State Security Service extort large protection money so that they can maintain their expensive living standards in Moscow, it is said.
They're raising money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized crime gangs.
Each layer of the bureaucracy - what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called "verticals of authority" - takes its share of the money that travels up the ladder.
The memo, sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published on Tuesday by WikiLeaks on its homepage.
The memo is based on sources whose names have been redacted.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still Moscow's mayor, and it accuses him of corruption.
He was fired by President Dmitry Medvedev in October, but there is little evidence that he has been cleaned up since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a well-known construction company, have repeatedly denied corruption allegations over the years, and he has won numerous libel suits against such allegations.
In September, he told a Russian TV station, when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: "It's crazy, it's dirty, it's filthy".
> An incredibly large number of Russians believe their society is corrupt, polls have shown.
But it is unusual for individuals to be named, as in the ambassador's report, and it is unheard of for this to be done by a diplomat of a foreign country.
"The direct connection of the government of Moscow with crime has led some to describe it as 'dysfunctional' and conclude that the government is more like a kleptocrat than a government", the memo says.
"Criminal elements enjoy a kryschna (a term from the criminal/mafia world, literally meaning 'roof' or 'shelter') that extends through the police, the State Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD) and the Prosecutor's Office as well as through the entire Moscow government bureaucracy.
Experts have discovered a three-tier structure within the criminal world of Moscow.
"Luzhkov is at the top".
"FSB, MVD and the militia are on the second level".
"Last to the ordinary criminals and the criminal inspectors at the lowest level".
"This is an incompetent system where criminal groups are filling a gap in some areas because the city is not offering any help".
The report goes on to say that the FSB is taking money from the biggest companies and that the police are arresting small businessmen.
One source, it is said, "said that Moscow's business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and FSB (and not from organized crime), as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than the criminals, but also because they are protected by the law".
"For this reason, protection by criminal gangs is not as much in demand as it once was".
The memo notes that while the fundraising is extensive, the protection itself is very modest; even those who pay are sometimes arrested.
Those who do not pay find their business very quickly closed - on one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about fighting corruption, but has also noted that he has made little progress.
The embassy memo contains descriptions of men going into the Kremlin with suitcases that were probably full of money.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to rely on the bureaucrats", Georgy Satarov, director of Indem, a Moscow-based expert commission, said in a recent interview.
"But he's part of this bureaucracy".
"It is not part of the political class because a political class no longer exists in Russia".
Without politicians, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he says, corruption is inevitable.
Nationally, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
The country ranks 154th in a recent study of global perceptions of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are ranked from "least corrupt" to "most corrupt").
The revelation of the US Embassy memo, which happened late night Moscow time, is sure to cause some controversy within the Russian government, although since Luzhkov can be blamed for Moscow's mistakes, it may also be a way for the Kremlin to claim that it is solving the problems.
In an interview with Larry King for CNN, Putin claimed that the WikiLeaks documents could be a fake and reacted angrily to the revelation that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth is that it's about our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic politics in this country", he said.
"But to be honest, we didn't expect it to happen with such arrogance, with such pressure and in such an unethical way, you know".
Khmer Rouge forced veterans to confront the past
In a dimly lit, concrete classroom with dirty and flaking walls, the headmaster of Anlong Veng High School remembers the man who built it, the later Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves the Ta Mok".
"He was a good leader and he took care of his people", said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where he has built hospitals and bridges, developed infrastructure and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, longtime supporters in Anlong Veng are being challenged.
In April, a local Truth and Reconciliation Forum allowed the victims to publicly confront the people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a textbook that for the first time tells children of former soldiers the story of the Khmer Rouge.
And in July, a joint UN-Cambodian tribunal convicted a former Khmer Rouge member for the first time when it sentenced the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these developments, fear grew among Khmer Rouge veteran Alnlong Vengs, making it difficult for them to reconcile and reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything", said Chhang Youk, head of the Documentation Center of Cambodia, an independent organization that researches the regime.
"For her, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil".
"It even splits families".
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died from disease, overwork or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-led government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement capitulated.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary waged guerrilla warfare from their base in the western mountains and jungles of Cambodia, Ta Mok drew the next generation to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-brokered peace agreement in 1993 led to the country's first democratic elections, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to flock to the government, leading to the surrender of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had not given in, was arrested by government forces in the Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in 2006 in Phnom Penh prison, where he was awaiting trial.
When their patrons no longer protected them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters fled to the grinding poverty of rural Cambodia, and many retained the movement in nostalgic memory.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local government posts because they laid down their arms, the common soldiers remained poor, uneducated peasants.
"These people have benefited very little from the surrender", said Sok Leang of the Justice and Reconciliation Center, which holds public forums across Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"They are rooted in the regime's utopian agrarian ideology".
"They grew up without any professional knowledge".
Lim, 55, who joined the RHM in 1974 as a teenager, fought in the jungle around Anlang Veng before settling down in 1998 to live a life of poverty as a rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good", he said.
"Ta Mok has given everyone something to eat".
"But now life is hard because we have to take care of ourselves".
The ongoing Khmer Rouge Tribunal has also raised concerns here.
Early next year, the court will try to bring to trial Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, and Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The mandate of the tribunal is to prosecute the old leaders and those who are primarily responsible for the atrocities, but it is not said whether it will pursue further acts beyond these four cases.
This has done little to allay the fears of Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district chief in Manteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told officials at the Cambodian Documentation Centre that she had led the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project that is believed to have killed thousands of forced laborers.
One hot evening, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to her log house on a dirty road outside Anlong Veng.
As the long sun shadows the withered grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss her Khmer Rouge past.
She said that if the court summoned her, she would refuse to go.
"Cambodia is living in peace and stability", she said.
"If there were no more persecutions, there would be war here".
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that the situation would become uncertain, the court would charge more suspects, although experts and historians debate this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past", he said.
But confronting the past is what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center.
"Reconciliation with Khmer times means putting the pieces together", he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken pieces together so that we can all understand".
The Centre created the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, the 75-page "History of Democratic Cambodia".
It distributed the book in June in Anlong Veng as an appendix to the Ministry of Education's history book for high school, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As is often the case in Cambodia, the young people in Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helps students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents were skeptical when he brought the book home to read.
"My family rejects many parts of the book and the court", he said.
"They're suspicious because they're not sure how many people will be convicted by the court".
Such resistance makes the process of reconciliation complex and complicated, said Sok Leang.
But the public forums, the textbook and the courts are gradually gaining influence", he said.
The Khmer Rouge still holds a powerful appeal here.
Up in the Dangrek Mountains, a path covered in bushes and plastic debris leads to a rectangle of black soot covered by a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned on a pile of hay here after he died in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a mobile phone saleswoman on the side of the road, said she didn't know much about the man who was burned here.
"But he has a strong spirit and many people here go to him to pray", she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday, and later that day she was going to Pol Pot's final resting place, where she would lay a bush of ripe bananas - hoping that it would bring her luck.
