Germany has drawn a red line which it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures have to be taken now - the old way of the euro will no longer exist after that date.
2013 will be the year of the birth of a new currency area, where countries that are in breach of the rules are severely punished, can be forced to declare insolvency and in this case the private sector has to bear some of the costs.
Germany is showing us that we must pursue a hard growth path, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improvement in productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as was proposed by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would be doing a disservice not to understand it.
It is not just about reducing the government deficit to 3% by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope the current turbulence will subside.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities that are offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of bringing order to one's own house has made its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it does not look like it will change.
Among the possibilities considered is that we would have to leave the euro area, which is full of countries with little credibility.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and recreational activities
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged suspension of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November led to much speculation about whether or not it was an unsportsmanlike act and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls for the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would be leading their group, the two players will meet the prescribed sanction in the next league match against Auxerre and thus enter the next phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee sanctioned the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, but rather a common occurrence in the world of football.
It's so widespread that it's part of the ethos - the unwritten rules that are followed in this sport.
Part of the debate surrounding the case is that it was a team from Real Madrid (which in its anthem proclaims "Noble Courage and Honor" and has punished its players for similar incidents on other occasions) that played the main role, and the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is whether this conduct, which is expressly prohibited by the statutes, is not contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute a breach of the rules.
In this case, the damage to sportsmanship should be investigated.
The spirit of the game defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of fair play is to avoid the opposing players taking unfair advantage of the opposing team.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we usually understand as foul play or rule-breaking, because the rule-breaking was not done secretly to avoid a penalty, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the infringers derived from the intentional fouls.
It should be emphasized here that neither the opponent was put at a disadvantage nor any advantage was taken for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club doesn't have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players can start the next round of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardise their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term, to some extent uncertain advantage, as the team may eventually drop out, and the players who do so are penalized and move on to the second card cycle, where they drop out with one less card than in the first cycle due to card overload.
This makes it less clear whether it is really an advantage.
In the end, such approaches are not against the spirit of the game, which includes strategic decisions to get the most out of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to avoid a penalty (this would indeed be a clear case of rule-breaking), they wanted to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic choice without evading or fleeing punishment.
Although the line between inventiveness and regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the controversy arose from two factors: because there were two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the transfer of the rule.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than aesthetic.
Offering to attract customers for group Christmas dinners in Barcelona
The dictatorship of the calendar is causing an avalanche of reservations to fall on the 16th and 17th of December this year.
The number of parties paid for by employees is increasing, and they don't want to spend more than 20 or 30 euros.
