He explained that China's climate change strategy has four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress was made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which included targets for reducing gas emissions, he said.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, the authorities of the provincial states have worked together with those of the central state and the municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient use of energy and emission reduction.
The Commissioner also said that the Commission had already started or completed several multiannual plans, both those funded by the Chinese government and those funded by other countries.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficiency Program, which has been in place for the past five years and has received investment from the United Nations (UN), government and private sources.
There is also a project at provincial level on climate change, another on replacing traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs and another on mitigation and adaptation, he explained.
Martin Krol, the scientific adviser to the government on climate change in the country, confirmed that China's efforts were far greater than would be generally assumed.
He pointed out that China's per capita emissions of greenhouse gases were six tons per person, while in the United States it was 100 tons, and China is responsible for nine percent of the total contribution to environmental pollution.
