US changes visa rules
Before the interview, the person must present himself at the visa application service, which reduces waiting times and costs.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa at the Embassy and Consulates of the United States of America will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves to the visa service (ASC) before their interview at the consulate.
The ASC staff will record the applicant's biometric data, which will be checked by the consulate before the interview.
The new method has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The overall cost of visa processing is reduced by no longer having to pay separately for the appointment, processing of the visa application and the transport service used to deliver the document.
The applicant makes only one single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for handlers and investors.
Those who only wish to renew their visas do not have to go to the consulate, but simply present themselves at the nearest ASC, where they are presented with their documents and fingerprinted.
As the biometric data is collected at the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the interview at the consulate will spend less time there than before.
Those who apply for the visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer have to pay the $26 service surcharge.
The new visa application procedure is based on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
