The discovery may support the theory that in hostile environments previously thought to be uninhabitable, human-like creatures may exist, and the hypothesis has been raised that they may evolve into intelligent creatures like humans if their living conditions improve.
It appears to be a microbe found at the bottom of Mono Lake in Yosemite National Park, California, in an environment that has been deemed too toxic for all imaginable life because of the lake's high arsenic content.
In some ways, the microbes use arsenic as a survival resource, and taking this ability into account increases the chances that there could be life like this on other planets that don't have our protective atmosphere.
When these organisms mix the arsenic, astrobiologists say, it is proved that "there is actually another life form, a second life form, different from the one we know".
The space agency will announce the actual reach of its fund at the press conference tomorrow, Thursday.
