Hacking with a Vengeance and Spying With a Purpose
The WikiLeaks affair has a double meaning.
On the one hand, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal which is only a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy which governs the relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes on an international level, and gives a foretaste of a future dominated by regression.
But we'll take it one step at a time.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by any intelligence agency of any nation is made up entirely of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits are nothing more than what you've been reading for months in any magazine (except those owned by Berlusconi), and the horrifyingly caricatured profile of Gaddafi has long been a source of entertainment for cabaret artists.
The rule that the secret dossiers must be only news already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you go to a library devoted to esoteric publications, you will find that each work (on the Grail, the Mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly repeats what has already been written in previous works.
This is not merely because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (nor because he does not know where to find news about the nonexistent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe in nothing but what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown's success mechanism.
So are the classified files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited in spirit) is also the head of the intelligence service (otherwise he could be anything, for example, editor at Libération), who only considers as true what he acknowledges.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department was the same as the one that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why such a fuss over the disclosures of these files?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows: that the embassies - at least since the end of the Second World War and since then also the heads of government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and have become, with the exception of a few small representative functions, spy centres.
Any casual viewer of detective films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore this.
However, the fact that it is being publicly repeated violates the duty of hypocrisy and serves to cast a bad light on American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that a random hacker can access the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Moreover, the scandal brings less victims than "executioners" into trouble.
But let's get to the deep nature of what happened.
Back in Orwell's day, you could harness all power like a Big Brother, controlling every move of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy could have been proved to be perfectly true, where one could control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway chosen and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But when you consider what's happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can't escape the control of a hacker, the control flow stops being one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the citizen's avenger - can unlock the secrets of power.
But how can a power sustain itself when it is no longer able to guard its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel has already said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is basically a secret free of secrets, since it reveals the public sphere; but to reveal, in the style of WikiLeaks, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets is to deprive her of any power.
WikiLeaks did not wrong Sarkozy or Merkel, but Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this insult to such a great power?
It is obvious that in future, states will no longer post any classified information online - that would be like putting a sign on a street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with today's technology, it is futile to hope to keep confidential telephone messages secret.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state is on a plane and has contacted one of his colleagues.
How could relationships be kept private and reserved for certain ears in the future?
I know that my prediction sounds like science fiction and romance at the moment, but I am forced to imagine the government agents, secretly moving along uncontrollable routes, carrying their messages nowhere but in their memory, and hiding the little written information they have in their shoes.
The information would be stored in a single copy in locked drawers: in fact, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology today is advancing like a cancer, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet is reconstructing a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analogue) videocassettes had enabled film researchers to study a film tape by tape, by rewinding from the back to the front and exposing all the secrets of the editing, whereas the (numerical) CDs nowadays allow nothing but to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. in macro proportions.
High-speed trains take three hours to get from Rome to Milan, whereas an airplane takes three and a half hours, including the changeover.
It is not unusual, therefore, that politics and communication technology are coming back to the car and the horse.
One last observation, please.
In the past, the press has tried to understand what secrets were forged between the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that are demanding confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France is making good on its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Treaty, it is time to examine the implementation of the rapidly solved financing commitments (also known as 'fast start' or early financing) made by the developing countries.
And already the crude French euphemisms have been exposed.
The Copenhagen Accord commits developing countries to provide 30 billion dollars between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged €7.2 billion over three years, France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million per year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU did everything to convince its partners of its commitment to fast-start financing: detailed progress reports from its Member States, press conference, major side events, distribution of brochures.
The operation of transparency is remarkable and appreciated for its own value: developing countries and civil society would like to see all developed countries doing the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if you look at the details, things are a little more complicated.
This money was to be 'new and additional' according to the Copenhagen Treaty, to ensure that additional effort was made without detriment to ODA.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain Member States, including France, blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark that he considers best.
The EU Commission, for example, has chosen to set the guideline for the 2009 programme: international financing will be maintained and 150 million will be added to it over three years as part of the 'fast start' funding.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of years or terms at the official development assistance level.
In contrast, France considered that the financing of 'all new projects' in 2010 was 'new and additional'.
In other words, there are no benchmarks for the previous year's expenditure or at the global level of official development aid.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease) - France claims to be honouring its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into grants and loans.
There is no rule yet, and each person chooses his own way of calculating.
Some, such as France, consider €1 borrowed to be equivalent to €1 donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to accept: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often emission-reduction projects based on the most efficient technology) can be justified, it is misleading to present the euro as the equivalent of a euro donated... Furthermore, only the cost of the loan to the donor country should be counted as a commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has no other reason than to "respect" its commitment of 420 million by taking 91.5% of the loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% (36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to see for yourself.
France is the only EU country that uses loans on a large scale.
Germany is asking for 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are meeting their obligations 100% with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends 1 euro to meet its obligations, France spends just 10 cents, and understands this as a similar commitment.
That's some trick!
In the short term, the French authorities are operating a double-dealing in their fast-start financing: on the one hand, with the development of the action over time, and on the other hand, with the reality of the financial commitment.
France succeeds in making people believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in accordance with its promises, thus saving 36.1 million euros.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (as it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative effect, firstly within the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries cannot be completely deceived...
The chapter on early financing is only a small issue in a relatively short time compared to the whole of the climate debate.
But it could be the last straw in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
Whatever the case, it is imperative that he learn his lesson from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting system for the years 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respect for its obligations and of balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
In particular, however, France could advance the debate on the controversial nature of long-term financing (another crucial issue which is currently being discussed): the question of the 'availability' or the accounting nature of its loans cannot be avoided.
France could change its position to be as progressive on the issues in dispute as it is on other things.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "traceability" and the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussion.
Alert - pesticide ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals a day, according to a study released Wednesday by the Générations Futures (formerly the Movement for the Protection of the Rights and Respect of Future Generations) Association.
The association, which states that its results "do not represent a statistical significance in view of the small number of samples analysed, but are illustrative of the problem under consideration", had bought between July and September the food normally consumed by a child of about ten years of age in the course of four meals plus a snack in the supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These typical meals - including the official recommendation of five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products, and one and a half liters of water a day - have been tested by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals, and other contaminants, as well as for dairy products.
The balance sheet is staggering: 81 chemicals, including 42 classified as possibly or probably carcinogenic and five classified as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 endocrine disrupting substances, according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical substance ingested are not exceeded in the majority of cases, the survey does a good job of highlighting the reality of potential exposure to carcinogens or endocrine disrupting substances", notes the association.
Even at breakfast, butter and tea with milk alone contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three that have been proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, contains traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to green beans from Kenya, including those used for lunch, which the study found to contain traces of an insecticide strictly prohibited in the EU.
Also, the ham, tuna, even the baguette and the gum were laced with pesticides and other chemicals.
The analysis of the tap water revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon steak was the "highest" with 34 chemical residues, and even the plastic plate used to heat the meal in the microwave was not uncontaminated.
The final risk of this "harmful cocktail" to the consumer "is likely to be underestimated", says the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed, in view of the urgency of the situation, a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the increase in civilization diseases.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
